# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: approximant
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:approximant/affricate] An **affricate** is a consonant that begins as a stop and releases as a fricative, generally with the same place of articulation (most often coronal).
[src:approximant/affricate] It is often difficult to decide if a stop and fricative form a single phoneme or a consonant pair.
[src:approximant/affricate] English has two affricate phonemes, /t͡ʃ/ and /d͡ʒ/, generally spelled *ch* and *j*, respectively.
[src:approximant/affricate] However, voiced affricates other than [d͡ʒ] are relatively uncommon.
[src:approximant/affricate] For several places of articulation they are not attested at all.
[src:approximant/affricate] Much less common are labiodental affricates, such as [p͡f] in German, Kinyarwanda and Izi, or velar affricates, such as [k͡x] in Tswana (written *kg*) or in High Alemannic Swiss German dialects.
[src:approximant/affricate] Worldwide, relatively few languages have affricates in these positions even though the corresponding stop consonants, [p] and [k], are common or virtually universal.
[src:approximant/affricate] Also less common are alveolar affricates where the fricative release is lateral, such as the [t͡ɬ] sound found in Nahuatl and Navajo.
[src:approximant/affricate] Some other Athabaskan languages, such as Dene Suline, have unaspirated, aspirated, and ejective series of affricates whose release may be dental, alveolar, postalveolar, or lateral: [t̪͡θ], [t̪͡θʰ], [t̪͡θʼ], [t͡s], [t͡sʰ], [t͡sʼ], [t͡ʃ], [t͡ʃʰ], [t͡ʃʼ], [t͡ɬ], [t͡ɬʰ], and [t͡ɬʼ].
[src:approximant/affricate] Affricates are transcribed in the International Phonetic Alphabet by a combination of two letters, one for the stop element and the other for the fricative element.
[src:approximant/affricate] In order to clarify that these form a single consonant, a tie bar may be used.
[src:approximant/affricate] The tie bar appears most commonly above the two letters, but may be placed under them if it fits better there, or simply because it is more legible.
[src:approximant/affricate] This is derived from the IPA convention of indicating other releases with a superscript.
[src:approximant/affricate] However, this convention is more typically used for a fricated release that is too brief to be considered a true affricate.
[src:approximant/affricate] Ligatures ⟨, , , /, ⟩ for the non-coronal affricates [pɸ] [bβ], [pf] [bv], [cç] [ɟʝ], [kx] [ɡɣ]/[gɣ], [qχ] [ɢʁ] have also been used.
[src:approximant/affricate] Any of these notations can be used to distinguish an affricate from a sequence of plosive plus fricative, which is contrastive in languages such as Polish.
[src:approximant/affricate] However, in languages where there is no such distinction within a syllable, such as English or Turkish, a simple sequence of letters such as ⟨tʃ⟩ is commonly used, with no overt indication that they form an affricate.
[src:approximant/affricate] In such cases the syllable boundary may be written to distinguish the plosive-fricative sequence in *petshop* /ˈpɛt.ʃɒp/ from the similar affricate in *ketchup* /ˈkɛtʃʌp/.
[src:approximant/affricate] In other phonetic transcription systems, such as the Americanist system, affricates may be transcribed with single letters.
[src:approximant/affricate] Single letters may also be used with phonemic transcription in IPA: [tʃ] and [dʒ] are sometimes transcribed with the symbols for the palatal stops, ⟨c⟩ and ⟨ɟ⟩, for example in the IPA *Handbook*.
[src:approximant/affricate] The exact phonetic difference varies between languages.
[src:approximant/affricate] In stop–fricative sequences, the stop has a release burst before the fricative starts; but in affricates, the fricative element *is* the release.
[src:approximant/affricate] Phonologically, stop–fricative sequences may have a syllable boundary between the two segments, but not necessarily.
[src:approximant/affricate] In English, /ts/ and /dz/ (*nuts*, *nods*) are considered phonemically stop–fricative sequences.
[src:approximant/affricate] They often contain a morpheme boundary (for example, *nuts* = *nut* + *s*).
[src:approximant/affricate] The English affricate phonemes /t͡ʃ/ and /d͡ʒ/ do not contain morpheme boundaries.
[src:approximant/affricate] The /t/ in 'worst shin' can be elided: [wɜː(ɹ)sʃɪn].
[src:approximant/affricate] Stop–fricatives can be distinguished acoustically from affricates by the rise time of the frication noise, which is shorter for affricates.
[src:approximant/affricate] When affricates are geminated, it is the duration of the plosive closure that is lengthened, not that of the frication.
[src:approximant/affricate] For example, /t͜sː/ is pronounced [tːs], not *[tsː].
[src:approximant/affricate] Polish has been reported to favour phonological gemination through rearticulation of the affricate, rather than the common method of lengthening the plosive closure.
[src:approximant/affricate] In the case of coronals, the symbols ⟨t, d⟩ are normally used for the stop portion of the affricate regardless of place.
[src:approximant/affricate] For example, ⟨t͡ʂ⟩ is commonly seen for ⟨ʈ͡ʂ⟩, ⟨t͡ʃ⟩ for ⟨t̠͡ʃ⟩ and ⟨t͡θ⟩ for ⟨t̪͡θ⟩.
[src:approximant/affricate] The exemplar languages are ones that have been reported to have these sounds, but in several cases, they may need confirmation.
[src:approximant/affricate] The Northwest Caucasian languages Abkhaz and Ubykh both contrast sibilant affricates at four places of articulation: alveolar, postalveolar, alveolo-palatal and retroflex.
[src:approximant/affricate] They also distinguish voiceless, voiced, and ejective affricates at each of these.
[src:approximant/affricate] When a language has only one type of affricate, it is usually a sibilant; this is the case in e.g.
[src:approximant/affricate] Arabic ([d̠ʒ]), most dialects of Spanish ([t̠ʃ]), and Thai ([tɕ]).
[src:approximant/affricate] Itene, Oro Win, Sangtam, and Wari' have a dental stop with bilabial trilled release [t̪ʙ̥].
[src:approximant/affricate] Although most affricates are homorganic, Navajo and Chiricahua Apache have a heterorganic alveolar-velar affricate [tx].
[src:approximant/affricate] Itene, Oro Win, Sangtam, and Wari' have a voiceless dental bilabially trilled affricate [t̪ʙ̥] (see Trilled affricate).
[src:approximant/affricate] Other heterorganic affricates are reported for Northern Sotho and other Bantu languages such as Phuthi, which has alveolar–labiodental affricates [tf] and [dv], and Sesotho, which has bilabial–palatoalveolar affricates [pʃ] and [bʒ].
[src:approximant/affricate] The coronal and dorsal places of articulation attested as ejectives as well: [tθʼ, tsʼ, tɬʼ, tʃʼ, tɕʼ, tʂʼ, c𝼆ʼ, kxʼ, k𝼄ʼ, qχʼ].
[src:approximant/affricate] Several Khoisan languages such as Taa are reported to have voiced ejective affricates, but these are actually *pre*-voiced: [dtsʼ, dtʃʼ].
[src:approximant/affricate] Affricates are also commonly aspirated: [ɱp̪fʰ, tθʰ, tsʰ, tɬʰ, tʃʰ, tɕʰ, tʂʰ], murmured: [ɱb̪vʱ, dðʱ, dzʱ, dɮʱ, dʒʱ, dʑʱ, dʐʱ], and prenasalized: [ⁿdz, ⁿtsʰ, ᶯɖʐ, ᶯʈʂʰ] (as in Hmong).
[src:approximant/affricate] Labialized, palatalized, velarized, and pharyngealized affricates are also common.
[src:approximant/affricate] Affricates may also have phonemic length, that is, affected by a chroneme, as in Italian and Karelian.
[src:approximant/affricate] In phonology, affricates tend to behave similarly to stops, taking part in phonological patterns that fricatives do not.
[src:approximant/affricate] Kehrein (2002) analyzes phonetic affricates as phonological stops.
[src:approximant/affricate] A sibilant or lateral (and presumably trilled) stop can be realized phonetically only as an affricate and so might be analyzed phonemically as a sibilant or lateral stop.
[src:approximant/affricate] In that analysis, affricates other than sibilants and laterals are a phonetic mechanism for distinguishing stops at similar places of articulation (like more than one labial, coronal, or dorsal place).
[src:approximant/affricate] For example, Chipewyan has laminal dental [t̪͡θ] vs. apical alveolar [t]; other languages may contrast velar [k] with palatal [c͡ç] and uvular [q͡χ].
[src:approximant/affricate] Affricates may also be a strategy to increase the phonetic contrast between aspirated or ejective and tenuis consonants.
[src:approximant/affricate] According to Kehrein (2002), no language contrasts a non-sibilant, non-lateral affricate with a stop at the same place of articulation and with the same phonation and airstream mechanism, such as /t̪/ and /t̪θ/ or /k/ and /kx/.
[src:approximant/affricate] In feature-based phonology, affricates are distinguished from stops by the feature [+delayed release].
[src:approximant/affricate] Affrication (sometimes called *affricatization*) is a sound change by which a consonant, usually a stop or fricative, changes into an affricate.
[src:approximant/affricate] In rare instances, a fricative–stop contour may occur.
[src:approximant/affricate] This is the case in dialects of Scottish Gaelic that have velar frication [ˣ] where other dialects have pre-aspiration.
[src:approximant/affricate] For example, in the Harris dialect there is *seachd* [ʃaˣkʰ] 'seven' and *ochd* [ɔˣkʰ] 'eight' (or [ʃax͜kʰ], [ɔx͜kʰ]).
[src:approximant/affricate] Richard Wiese argues this is the case for word-initial fricative-plosive sequences in German, and coined the term **suffricate** for such contours.
[src:approximant/affricate] Awngi has 2 suffricates /s͡t/ and /ʃ͡t/ according to some analyses.
[src:approximant/airflow] In engineering, airflow is a measurement of the amount of air per unit of time that flows through a particular device.
[src:approximant/airflow] It can be described as a volumetric flow rate (volume of air per unit time) or a mass flow rate (mass of air per unit time).
[src:approximant/airflow] What relates both forms of description is the air density, which is a function of pressure and temperature through the ideal gas law.
[src:approximant/airflow] The flow of air can be induced through mechanical means (such as by operating an electric or manual fan) or can take place passively, as a function of pressure differentials present in the environment.
[src:approximant/airflow] Like any fluid, air may exhibit both laminar and turbulent flow patterns.
[src:approximant/airflow] Laminar flow occurs when air can flow smoothly, and exhibits a parabolic velocity profile; turbulent flow occurs when there is an irregularity (such as a disruption in the surface across which the fluid is flowing), which alters the direction of movement.
[src:approximant/airflow] Turbulent flow exhibits a flat velocity profile.
[src:approximant/airflow] Velocity profiles of fluid movement describe the spatial distribution of instantaneous velocity vectors across a given cross section.
[src:approximant/airflow] The size and shape of the geometric configuration that the fluid is traveling through, the fluid properties (such as viscosity), physical disruptions to the flow, and engineered components (e.g. pumps) that add energy to the flow are factors that determine what the velocity profile looks like.
[src:approximant/airflow] Generally, in encased flows, instantaneous velocity vectors are larger in magnitude in the middle of the profile due to the effect of friction from the material of the pipe, duct, or channel walls on nearby layers of fluid.
[src:approximant/airflow] In tropospheric atmospheric flows, velocity increases with elevation from ground level due to friction from obstructions like trees and hills slowing down airflow near the surface.
[src:approximant/airflow] The level of friction is quantified by a parameter called the "roughness length." Streamlines connect velocities and are tangential to the instantaneous direction of multiple velocity vectors.
[src:approximant/airflow] They can be curved and do not always follow the shape of the container.
[src:approximant/airflow] Additionally, they only exist in steady flows, i.e. flows whose velocity vectors do not change over time.
[src:approximant/airflow] In a laminar flow, all particles of the fluid are traveling in parallel lines which gives rise to parallel streamlines.
[src:approximant/airflow] In a turbulent flow, particles are traveling in random and chaotic directions which gives rise to curved, spiraling, and often intersecting streamlines.
[src:approximant/airflow] The Reynolds number, a ratio indicating the relationship between viscous and inertial forces in a fluid, can be used to predict the transition from laminar to turbulent flow.
[src:approximant/airflow] Laminar flows occur at low Reynold's numbers where viscous forces dominate, and turbulent flows occur at high Reynold's numbers where inertial forces dominate.
[src:approximant/airflow] The range of Reynold's number that defines each type of flow depends on whether the air is moving through a pipe, wide duct, open channel, or around airfoils.
[src:approximant/airflow] Reynold's number can also characterize an object (for example, a particle under the effect of gravitational settling) moving through a fluid.
[src:approximant/airflow] This number and related concepts can be applied to studying flow in systems of all scales.
[src:approximant/airflow] Transitional flow is a mixture of turbulence in the center of the velocity profile and laminar flow near the edges.
[src:approximant/airflow] Each of these three flows have distinct mechanisms of frictional energy losses that give rise to different behavior.
[src:approximant/airflow] As a result, different equations are used to predict and quantify the behavior of each type of flow.
[src:approximant/airflow] The speed at which a fluid flows past an object varies with distance from the object's surface.
[src:approximant/airflow] The region surrounding an object where the air speed approaches zero is known as the boundary layer.
[src:approximant/airflow] It is here that surface friction most affects flow; irregularities in surfaces may affect boundary layer thickness, and hence act to disrupt flow.
[src:approximant/airflow] Airflow can also be described in terms of air changes per hour (ACH), indicating full replacement of the volume of air filling the space in question.
[src:approximant/airflow] This unit is frequently used in the field of building science, with higher ACH values corresponding to leakier envelopes which are typical of older buildings that are less tightly sealed.
[src:approximant/airflow] The instrument that measures airflow is called an airflow meter.
[src:approximant/airflow] Anemometers are also used to measure wind speed and indoor airflow.
[src:approximant/airflow] There are a variety of types, including straight probe anemometers, designed to measure air velocity, differential pressure, temperature, and humidity; rotating vane anemometers, used for measuring air velocity and volumetric flow; and hot-sphere anemometers.
[src:approximant/airflow] Anemometers may use ultrasound or resistive wire to measure the energy transfer between the measurement device and the passing particles.
[src:approximant/airflow] A hot-wire anemometer, for example, registers decreases in wire temperature, which can be translated into airflow velocity by analyzing the rate of change.
[src:approximant/airflow] Convective cooling is a function of airflow rate, and the electrical resistance of most metals is dependent upon the temperature of the metal, which is affected by the convective cooling.
[src:approximant/airflow] Engineers have taken advantage of these physical phenomena in the design and use of hot-wire anemometers.
[src:approximant/airflow] Some tools are capable of calculating air flow, wet bulb temperature, dew point, and turbulence.
[src:approximant/airflow] Air flow can be simulated using computational fluid dynamics (CFD) modeling, or observed experimentally through the operation of a wind tunnel**.** This may be used to predict airflow patterns around automobiles, aircraft, and marine craft, as well as air penetration of a building envelope.
[src:approximant/airflow] Because CFD models "also track the flow of solids through a system," they can be used for analysis of pollution concentrations in indoor and outdoor environments.
[src:approximant/airflow] Particulate matter generated indoors generally comes from cooking with oil and combustion activities such as burning candles or firewood.
[src:approximant/airflow] One type of equipment that regulates the airflow in ducts is called a damper.
[src:approximant/airflow] The damper can be used to increase, decrease or completely stop the flow of air.
[src:approximant/airflow] A more complex device that can not only regulate the airflow but also has the ability to generate and condition airflow is an air handler.
[src:approximant/airflow] Fans also generate flows by "producing air flows with high volume and low pressure (although higher than ambient pressure)." This pressure differential induced by the fan is what causes air to flow.
[src:approximant/airflow] The direction of airflow is determined by the direction of the pressure gradient.
[src:approximant/airflow] Total or static pressure rise, and therefore by extension airflow rate, is determined primarily by the fan speed measured in revolutions per minute (RPM).
[src:approximant/airflow] In control of HVAC systems to modulate the airflow rate, one typically changes the fan speed, which often come in 3-category settings such as low, medium, and high.
[src:approximant/airflow] Measuring the airflow is necessary in many applications such as ventilation (to determine how much air is being replaced), pneumatic conveying (to control the air velocity and phase of transport) and engines (to control the Air–fuel ratio).
[src:approximant/airflow] Aerodynamics is the branch of fluid dynamics (physics) that is specifically concerned with the measurement, simulation, and control of airflow.
[src:approximant/airflow] Managing airflow is of concern to many fields, including meteorology, aeronautics, medicine, mechanical engineering, civil engineering, environmental engineering and building science.
[src:approximant/airflow] In building science, airflow is often addressed in terms of its desirability, for example in contrasting ventilation and infiltration.
[src:approximant/airflow] Ventilation is defined as the desired flow of fresh outdoor supply air to another, typically indoor, space, along with the simultaneous expulsion of exhaust air from indoors to the outdoors.
[src:approximant/airflow] This may be achieved through mechanical means (i.e. the use of a louver or damper for air intake and a fan to induce flow through ductwork) or through passive strategies (also known as natural ventilation).
[src:approximant/airflow] While natural ventilation has economic benefits over mechanical ventilation because it typically requires far less operational energy consumption, it can only be utilized during certain times of day and under certain outdoor conditions.
[src:approximant/airflow] By contrast, air infiltration is characterized as the uncontrolled influx of air through an inadequately-sealed building envelope, usually coupled with unintentional leakage of conditioned air from the interior of a building to the exterior.
[src:approximant/airflow] Buildings may be ventilated using mechanical systems, passive systems or strategies, or a combination of the two.
[src:approximant/airflow] Mechanical ventilation uses fans to induce flow of air into and through a building.
[src:approximant/airflow] Duct configuration and assembly affect air flow rates through the system.
[src:approximant/airflow] Dampers, valves, joints and other geometrical or material changes within a duct can lead to flow pressure (energy) losses.
[src:approximant/airflow] Passive ventilation strategies take advantage of inherent characteristics of air, specifically thermal buoyancy and pressure differentials, to evacuate exhaust air from within a building.
[src:approximant/airflow] Stack effect equates to using chimneys or similar tall spaces with openings near the top to passively draw exhaust air up and out of the space, thanks to the fact that air will rise when its temperature increases (as the volume increases and pressure decreases).
[src:approximant/airflow] Wind-driven passive ventilation relies on building configuration, orientation, and aperture distribution to take advantage of outdoor air movement.
[src:approximant/airflow] Cross-ventilation requires strategically-positioned openings aligned with local wind patterns.
[src:approximant/airflow] Airflow is a factor of concern when designing to meet occupant thermal comfort standards (such as ASHRAE 55).
[src:approximant/airflow] Varying rates of air movement may positively or negatively impact individuals’ perception of warmth or coolness, and hence their comfort.
[src:approximant/airflow] Air velocity interacts with air temperature, relative humidity, radiant temperature of surrounding surfaces and occupants, and occupant skin conductivity, resulting in particular thermal sensations.
[src:approximant/airflow] Sufficient, properly-controlled and designed airflow (ventilation) is important for overall indoor environmental quality (IEQ) and indoor air quality (IAQ), in that it provides the necessary supply of fresh air and effectively evacuates exhaust air.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] In phonetics, the **airstream mechanism** is the method by which airflow is created in the vocal tract.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Along with phonation and articulation, it is one of three main components of speech production.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] The airstream mechanism is mandatory for most sound production and constitutes the first part of this process, which is called **initiation**.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] There are also methods of making sounds that do not require the glottis.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Any of the three principal initiators − diaphragm, glottis or tongue − may act by either increasing or decreasing the pressure generating the airstream.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] These changes in pressure often correspond to outward and inward airflow, and are therefore termed *egressive* and *ingressive* respectively.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] That leaves pulmonic ingressive and lingual (velaric) egressive as the only two airstream mechanisms produced by the three main initiators that are not found lexically in the world.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] These mechanisms may be combined into airstream contours, such as clicks which release into ejectives.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Most other languages utilize at most two airstream mechanisms.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] In interjections, the other two mechanisms may be employed.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] For example, in countries as diverse as Sweden, Turkey, and Togo, a pulmonic ingressive ("gasped" or "inhaled") vowel is used for back-channeling or to express agreement, and in France a lingual egressive (a "spurt") is used to express dismissal.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] The only language where such sounds are known to be contrastive in normal vocabulary is the extinct ritual language Damin (also the only language outside Africa with clicks); however, Damin appears to have been intentionally designed to differ from normal speech.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Initiation by means of the lungs (actually the diaphragm and ribs) is called **pulmonic** initiation.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] The vast majority of sounds used in human languages are pulmonic egressives.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] In most languages, including all the languages of Europe (excluding the Caucasus), all phonemes are pulmonic egressives.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] The only attested use of a phonemic pulmonic ingressive is a lateral fricative in Damin, a ritual language formerly used by speakers of Lardil in Australia.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] This can be written with the extended version of the International Phonetic Alphabet as [ɬ↓ʔ]. !Xóõ has ingression as a phonetic detail in one series of its clicks, which are *ingressive voiceless nasals with delayed aspiration*, [↓ŋ̊ʘʰ ↓ŋ̊ǀʰ ↓ŋ̊ǁʰ ↓ŋ̊!ʰ ↓ŋ̊ǂʰ].
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Peter Ladefoged considers these to be among the most difficult sounds in the world.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Other languages, for example in Taiwan, have been claimed to have pulmonic ingressives, but these claims have either proven to be spurious or to be occasional phonetic detail.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] In interjections, but not in normal words, pulmonic ingressive vowels or words occur on all continents.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] This is commonly done for back-channeling (as with [ə↓] in Ewe) or affirmation (as with [ɸʷ↓] in Swedish).
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] In English, an audible intake of breath, [hːː↓], or an indrawn consonant such as [tʰ↓] or [p͡t↓] is used in a conversation to indicate that someone is about to speak or is preparing to continue speaking.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] In some languages, such as Finnish and Amharic, entire phrases may be uttered with an ingressive airstream.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] It is possible to initiate airflow in the upper vocal tract by means of the vocal cords or glottis.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] This is known as **glottalic** initiation.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] For egressive glottalic initiation, one lowers the glottis (as if to sing a low note), closes it as for a glottal stop, and then raises it, building up pressure in the oral cavity and upper trachea.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Glottalic egressives are called **ejectives**.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] The glottis must be fully closed to form glottalic egressives, or the air column would flow backwards over it; it is therefore impossible to pronounce voiced ejectives.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Ejective allophones of voiceless stops occur in many varieties of English at the ends of intonation units.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] For ingressive glottalic initiation, the sequence of actions performed in glottalic pressure initiation is reversed: one raises the glottis (as if to sing a high note), closes it, and then lowers it to create suction in the upper trachea and oral cavity.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Glottalic ingressives are called **implosives**, although they may involve zero airflow rather than actual inflow.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Because the air column would flow forwards over the descending glottis, it is not necessary to fully close it, and implosives may be voiced; indeed, voiceless implosives are exceedingly rare.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] It is usual for implosives to be voiced.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Instead of keeping the glottis tightly closed, it is tensed but left slightly open to allow a thin stream of air through.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Unlike pulmonic voiced sounds, in which a stream of air passes through a usually-fixed glottis, in voiced implosives a mobile glottis passes over a nearly motionless air column to cause vibration of the vocal cords.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Phonations that are more open than modal voice, such as breathy voice, are not conducive to glottalic sounds because in these the glottis is held relatively open, allowing air to readily flow through and preventing a significant pressure difference from building up behind the articulator.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Because the oral cavity is so much smaller than the lungs, vowels and approximants cannot be pronounced with glottalic initiation.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] So-called glottalized vowels and other sonorants use the more common pulmonic egressive airstream mechanism.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] There is no clear divide between pulmonic and glottalic sounds.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Some languages may have consonants which are intermediate.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] For example, glottalized consonants in London English, such as the *t* in *rat* [ˈɹæʔt], may be weakly ejective.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Similarly, fully voiced stops in languages such as Thai, Zulu, and Maidu are weakly implosive.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] This ambiguity does not occur with the next airstream mechanism, lingual, which is clearly distinct from pulmonic sounds.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] The third form of initiation in human language is **lingual** or **velaric** initiation, where a sound is produced by a closure at two places of articulation, and the airstream is formed by movement of the body of the tongue.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Lingual stops are more commonly known as **clicks**, and are almost universally ingressive.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] The word *lingual* is derived from Latin *lingua*, which means tongue.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] To produce a lingual ingressive airstream, first close the vocal tract at two places: at the back of the tongue, as in a velar or uvular stop, and simultaneously with the front of the tongue or the lips, as in a coronal or bilabial stop.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] These holds may be voiceless, voiced, or nasalized.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Then lower the body of the tongue to rarefy the air above it.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] The closure at the front of the tongue is opened first, as the click "release"; then the closure at the back is released for the pulmonic or glottalic click "accompaniment" or "efflux".
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] This may be aspirated, affricated, or even ejective.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Even when not ejective, it is not uncommon for the glottis to be closed as well, for a triply articulated consonant, and this third closure is released last to produce a glottalized click.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Clicks are found in very few languages, notably the Khoisan languages of southern Africa and some nearby tongues such as Zulu.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] They are more often found in extra-linguistic contexts, such as the "tsk tsk" sound many Westerners use to express regret or pity (a dental click), or the clucking noise used by many equestrians to urge on their horses (a lateral click).
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Lingual egressive initiation is performed by reversing the sequence of a lingual ingressive: the front and back of the tongue (or lips and back of the tongue) seal off the vocal cavity, and the cheeks and middle of the tongue move inward and upward to increase oral pressure.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] The only attested use of a lingual egressive is a bilabial egressive "spurt" in Damin.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Transcribing this also requires the use of the Extended IPA, [ʘ↑].
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Since the air pocket used to initiate lingual consonants is so small, it is not thought to be possible to produce lingual fricatives, vowels, or other sounds which require continuous airflow.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Clicks may be voiced, but they are more easily nasalized.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] This may be because the vocal cavity behind the rearmost closure, behind which the air passing through the glottis for voicing must be contained, is so small that clicks cannot be voiced for long.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Allowing the airstream to pass through the nose enables a longer production.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Nasal clicks involve a combination of lingual and pulmonic mechanisms.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] The velum is lowered so as to direct pulmonic airflow through the nasal cavity during the lingual initiation.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] This nasal airflow may itself be egressive or ingressive, independently of the lingual initiation of the click.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Nasal clicks may be voiced, but are very commonly unvoiced and even aspirated, which is rare for purely pulmonic nasals.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] In some treatments, complex clicks are posited to have airstream contours, in which the airstream changes between the front (click) and rear (non-click) release.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] There are two attested types: Linguo-pulmonic consonants, where the rear release is a uvular obstruent such as [q] or [χ]; and linguo-glottalic consonants, where the rear release is an ejective such as [qʼ] or [qχʼ].
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Not only are simultaneous (rather than contour) implosive clicks possible, i.e. velar (e.g. [ɠ͡ǀ]), uvular ([ʛ͡ǀ]), and *de facto* front-closed palatal ([ʄ͡ǀ]), but velar implosive clicks are easier to produce than modally voiced clicks.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] However, they are not attested in any language.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Consonants may be pronounced without any airstream mechanism.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] These are a subset of *percussive* consonants, where sound is generated by one speech organ striking another.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] The only percussive confirmed to be used in normal speech is a tongue slap that appears allophonically in the release of alveolar clicks in the Sandawe language of Tanzania.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] (See Alveolar click § Percussive release and Palatal click § Percussive release.) There is also a speech register in Pirahã in which the tongue is released from a lateral flap [ɺ] to make a sublaminal strike of the lower lip [¡᫥].
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] Tap and flap consonants in general are described as percussive sounds, but in an articulatory sense; the airstream mechanism is still pulmonic because the sound is generated by a (percussive) interruption of a pulmonic airflow.
[src:approximant/airstream-mechanism] The abrupt releases of other pulmonic consonants have also been described as percussive, for example the audible velar release often heard in a velar nasal before a vowel, [ŋᶢ].
[src:approximant/allophone] In phonology, an **allophone** (/ˈæləˌfoʊn/ ⓘ; from Ancient Greek ἄλλος*(*állos*)* 'other' and φωνή*(*phōnḗ*)* 'voice, sound') is one of multiple possible spoken sounds, or *phones*, used to pronounce a single phoneme in a particular language.
[src:approximant/allophone] For example, in English, the voiceless plosive [t] (as in *stop* [ˈstɒp]) and the aspirated form [tʰ] (as in *top* [ˈtʰɒp]) are allophones for the phoneme /t/, while these two are considered to be different phonemes in some languages such as Central Thai.
[src:approximant/allophone] Similarly, in Spanish, [d] (as in *dolor* [doˈloɾ]) and [ð] (as in *nada* [ˈnaða]) are allophones for the phoneme /d/, while these two are considered to be different phonemes in English (as in the difference between *dare* and *there*).
[src:approximant/allophone] The specific allophone selected in a given situation is often predictable from the phonetic context, with such allophones being called **positional variants**, but some allophones occur in free variation.
[src:approximant/allophone] Replacing a sound by another allophone of the same phoneme usually does not change the meaning of a word, but the result may sound non-native or even unintelligible.
[src:approximant/allophone] Native speakers of a given language perceive one phoneme in the language as a single distinctive sound and are "both unaware of and even shocked by" the allophone variations that are used to pronounce single phonemes.
[src:approximant/allophone] The term "allophone" was coined by Benjamin Lee Whorf circa 1929.
[src:approximant/allophone] In doing so, he is thought to have placed a cornerstone in consolidating early phoneme theory.
[src:approximant/allophone] Trager and Bernard Bloch in a 1941 paper on English phonology and went on to become part of standard usage within the American structuralist tradition.
[src:approximant/allophone] Each time a speaker vocalizes a phoneme, they pronounce it differently from previous iterations.
[src:approximant/allophone] There is debate regarding how real and universal phonemes are (see phoneme for details).
[src:approximant/allophone] Only some of the variation is perceptible to listeners speakers.
[src:approximant/allophone] There are two types of allophones: complementary allophones and free-variant allophones.
[src:approximant/allophone] Complementary allophones are not interchangeable.
[src:approximant/allophone] If context requires a speaker to use a specific allophone for a given phoneme (that is, using a different allophone would confuse listeners), the possible allophones are said to be *complementary*.
[src:approximant/allophone] Each allophone from a complementary set is used in a specific phonetic context and may be involved in a phonological process.
[src:approximant/allophone] Otherwise, allophones are *free-variant*; speakers choose an allophone by habit or preference.
[src:approximant/allophone] An **allotone** is a tonic allophone, such as the neutral tone in Standard Mandarin.
[src:approximant/allophone] There are many allophonic processes in English: lack of plosion, nasal plosion, partial devoicing of sonorants, complete devoicing of sonorants, partial devoicing of obstruents, lengthening and shortening vowels, and retraction.
[src:approximant/allophone] Since the choice among allophones is rarely under conscious control, few people realize their existence.
[src:approximant/allophone] A flame that is held in front of the lips while those words are spoken flickers more for the aspirated *nitrate* than for the unaspirated *night rate*.
[src:approximant/allophone] The difference can also be felt by holding the hand in front of the lips.
[src:approximant/allophone] For a Mandarin-speaker, for whom /t/ and /tʰ/ are separate phonemes, the English distinction is much more obvious than for an English-speaker, who has learned since childhood to ignore the distinction.
[src:approximant/allophone] One may notice the (dialect-dependent) allophones of English /l/ such as the (palatal) alveolar "light" [l] of *leaf* [ˈliːf] as opposed to the velar alveolar "dark" [ɫ] in *feel* [ˈfiːɫ] found in the U.S. and Southern England.
[src:approximant/allophone] The difference is much more obvious to a Turkish-speaker, for whom /l/ and /ɫ/ are separate phonemes, than to an English speaker, for whom they are allophones of a single phoneme.
[src:approximant/allophone] These descriptions are more sequentially broken down in the next section.
[src:approximant/allophone] Peter Ladefoged, a renowned phonetician, clearly explains the consonant allophones of English in a precise list of statements to illustrate the language behavior.
[src:approximant/allophone] Some of these rules apply to all the consonants of English; the first item on the list deals with consonant length, items 2 through 18 apply to only selected groups of consonants, and the last item deals with the quality of a consonant.
[src:approximant/allophone] Voiceless stops /p, t, k/ are aspirated when they come at the beginning of a syllable, such as in words like "pip, test, kick" [pʰɪp, tʰɛst, kʰɪk].
[src:approximant/allophone] We can compare this with voiceless stops that are not syllable initial like "stop" [stɑp].
[src:approximant/allophone] The /t/ voiceless stop follows the /s/ (fricative) here.
[src:approximant/allophone] Voiced obstruents, which include stops and fricatives, such as /b, d, ɡ, v, ð, z, ʒ/, that come at the end of an utterance like /v/ in "improve" or before a voiceless sound like /d/ in "add two") are only briefly voiced during the articulation.
[src:approximant/allophone] Voiced stops and affricates /b, d, ɡ, dʒ/ in fact occur as partially devoiced at the beginning of a syllable unless immediately preceded by a voiced sound, in which the voiced sound carries over.
[src:approximant/allophone] Approximants (in English, these include /w, r, j, l/) are partially devoiced when they occur after syllable-initial /p, t, k/ like in "play, twin, cue" [pʰl̥eɪ, tʰw̥ɪn, kʰj̥u].
[src:approximant/allophone] Voiceless stops and affricates /p, t, k, tʃ/ are longer than their voiced counterparts /b, d, ɡ, dʒ/ when situated at the end of a syllable.
[src:approximant/allophone] Try comparing "cap" to "cab" or "back" to "bag".
[src:approximant/allophone] When a stop comes before another stop, the explosion of air only follows after the second stop, illustrated in words like "apt" [æp̚t] and "rubbed" [rʌb̚d].
[src:approximant/allophone] Many English accents produce a glottal stop in syllables that end with voiceless stops.
[src:approximant/allophone] Some examples include pronunciations of "tip, pit, kick" [tʰɪʔp, pʰɪʔt, kʰɪʔk].
[src:approximant/allophone] Some accents of English use a glottal stop in place of a /t/ when it comes before an alveolar nasal in the same word (as opposed to in the next word), such as in the word "beaten" [ˈbiːʔn̩].
[src:approximant/allophone] Nasals become syllabic, or their own syllable, only when immediately following an obstruent (as opposed to just any consonant), such as in the words "leaden, chasm" [ˈlɛdn̩, ˈkæzm̩].
[src:approximant/allophone] Take in comparison "kiln, film"; in most accents of English, the nasals are not syllabic.
[src:approximant/allophone] The lateral /l/, however, is syllabic at the end of the word when immediately following any consonant, like in "paddle, whistle" [ˈpʰædl̩, ˈwɪsl̩].
[src:approximant/allophone] Alveolar stops become voiced taps when they occur between two vowels, as long as the second vowel is unstressed.
[src:approximant/allophone] Take for instance mainly American English pronunciations like "fatty, data, daddy, many" [ˈfæɾi, ˈdeɪɾə, ˈdæɾi, ˈmɛɾ̃i].
[src:approximant/allophone] All alveolar consonants assimilate to dentals when occurring before a dental.
[src:approximant/allophone] This also applies across word boundaries, for example "at this" [ˈæt̪ ðɪs].
[src:approximant/allophone] Alveolar stops are reduced or omitted when between two consonants.
[src:approximant/allophone] Some examples include "most people" (can be written either as [ˈmoʊs ˈpʰipl̩] or [ˈmoʊst ˈpʰipl̩] with the IPA, where the [t] is inaudible, and "sand paper, grand master", where the [d] is inaudible.
[src:approximant/allophone] A consonant is shortened when it is before an identical consonant, such as in "big game" or "top post".
[src:approximant/allophone] A homorganic voiceless stop may be inserted after a nasal before a voiceless fricative followed by an unstressed vowel in the same word.
[src:approximant/allophone] For example, a bilabial voiceless plosive /p/ can be detected in the word "something" [ˈsʌmpθɪŋ] even though it is orthographically not indicated.
[src:approximant/allophone] However, the following vowel must be unstressed.
[src:approximant/allophone] Velar stops /k, ɡ/ become more front when the following vowel sound in the same syllable becomes more front.
[src:approximant/allophone] The lateral /l/ is velarized at the end of a word when it comes after a vowel as well as before a consonant.
[src:approximant/allophone] There are many examples for allophones in languages other than English.
[src:approximant/allophone] Typically, languages with a small phoneme inventory allow for quite a lot of allophonic variation: examples are Hawaiian and Pirahã.
[src:approximant/allophone] Since phonemes are abstractions of speech sounds, not the sounds themselves, they have no direct phonetic transcription.
[src:approximant/allophone] When they are realized without much allophonic variation, a simple broad transcription is used.
[src:approximant/allophone] However, when there are complementary allophones of a phoneme, the allophony becomes significant and things then become more complicated.
[src:approximant/allophone] If only one of the allophones is simple to transcribe, in the sense of not requiring diacritics, that representation is often chosen for the phoneme.
[src:approximant/allophone] However, there may be several such allophones, or the linguist might prefer greater precision than that allows.
[src:approximant/allophone] In such cases, a common convention is to use the "elsewhere condition" to decide the allophone that stands for the phoneme.
[src:approximant/allophone] The "elsewhere" allophone is the one that remains once the conditions for the others are described by phonological rules.
[src:approximant/allophone] For example, English has both oral and nasal allophones of its vowels.
[src:approximant/allophone] The pattern is that vowels are nasal only before a nasal consonant in the same syllable; elsewhere, they are oral.
[src:approximant/allophone] Therefore, by the "elsewhere" convention, the oral allophones are considered basic, and nasal vowels in English are considered to be allophones of oral phonemes.
[src:approximant/allophone] In different cases, an allophone may be chosen to represent its phoneme because it is more common in the languages of the world than the other allophones.
[src:approximant/allophone] This is because it reflects the historical origin of the phoneme, or it gives a more balanced look to a chart of the phonemic inventory.
[src:approximant/allophone] An alternative, which is commonly used for archiphonemes, is to use a capital letter, such as /N/ for [m], [n], [ŋ].
[src:approximant/allophone] In rare cases, a linguist may represent phonemes with abstract symbols, such as dingbats, to avoid privileging any particular allophone.
[src:approximant/alveolar-approximant] A **voiced alveolar approximant** is a type of consonantal sound used in some spoken languages.
[src:approximant/alveolar-approximant] It is familiar to most English-speakers as the ⟨r⟩ sound in ***r**ose* (though typically § postalveolar).
[src:approximant/alveolar-approximant] The symbol in the International Phonetic Alphabet that represents it is ⟨ɹ⟩, a lowercase Latin letter ⟨r⟩ rotated 180 degrees.
[src:approximant/alveolar-approximant] Some languages have a voiced (post)alveolar approximant that is acoustically distinct from a typical [ɹ], which has variously been described as being '[z]-like,' 'non-rhotic', or 'non-sulcalized'.
[src:approximant/alveolar-approximant] Some authors have reported the distinction as one of active articulation, with the formerly mentioned sound being classified as laminal, while a typical [ɹ] is distinguished as apical; though other authors have reported sounds of this type as being explicitly apical.
[src:approximant/alveolar-approximant] Somewhat less controversially, the distinction may also be made as a featural classing, between a 'rhotic approximant' and a 'spirant approximant' or 'frictionless continuant'.
[src:approximant/alveolar-approximant] These two latter terms are now used synonymously, though both recall older terms with slightly different meanings; they are now defined as being non-rhotic, non-lateral, non-semivowel approximants.
[src:approximant/alveolar-approximant] The International Phonetic Alphabet has no symbol to represent this sound, but possible transcriptions with diacritics include ⟨z̞⟩ (a lowered [z]) and ⟨ð̠˕⟩ (a lowered and retracted [ð]), both of which have been used in literature.
[src:approximant/alveolar-approximant] Several symbols have been proposed to represent this sound, but none have become widely accepted.
[src:approximant/alveolar-approximant] In Sinological circles, the symbol ⟨ɿ⟩ has also been used for this sound, where it has often been referred to as an 'apical vowel'.
[src:approximant/alveolar-approximant] The most common sound represented by the letter *r* in English is the **voiced postalveolar approximant**, pronounced further back than a typical [ɹ] and transcribed more precisely in IPA as ⟨ɹ̠⟩, but ⟨ɹ⟩ is often used for convenience in its place.
[src:approximant/alveolar-approximant] For further ease of typesetting, English phonemic transcriptions might use the symbol ⟨r⟩ even though this symbol represents the alveolar trill in phonetic transcription.
[src:approximant/alveolar-approximant] The voiced velar bunched approximant [ɹ̈], often called *bunched* or *molar r*, sounds remarkably similar to the postalveolar approximant, as does the voiced retroflex approximant [ɻ].
[src:approximant/alveolar-approximant] As an allophone of other rhotic sounds, [ɹ] occurs in Edo, Fula, Murrinh-patha, and Palauan.
[src:approximant/alveolar-consonant] The International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA) does not have separate symbols for the alveolar consonants.
[src:approximant/alveolar-consonant] Rather, the same symbol is used for all coronal places of articulation that are not palatalized like English palato-alveolar *sh*, or retroflex.
[src:approximant/alveolar-consonant] The bare letters [s, t, n, l], etc. cannot be assumed to specifically represent alveolars.
[src:approximant/alveolar-consonant] The language may not make such distinctions, such that two or more coronal places of articulation are found allophonically, or the transcription may simply be too broad to distinguish dental from alveolar.
[src:approximant/alveolar-consonant] If it is necessary to specify a consonant as alveolar, a diacritic from the Extended IPA may be used: [s͇, t͇, n͇, l͇], *etc.*, though that could also mean extra-retracted.
[src:approximant/alveolar-consonant] The letters ⟨s, t, n, l⟩ are frequently called 'alveolar,' and the examples from the languages below are all alveolar sounds.
[src:approximant/alveolar-consonant] Northwest Mekeo lacks coronal consonants entirely.
[src:approximant/alveolar-consonant] A few languages on Bougainville Island and around Puget Sound, such as Makah, lack nasals and therefore [n] but have [t].
[src:approximant/alveolar-consonant] Colloquial Samoan, however, lacks both [t] and [n] but has a lateral alveolar approximant /l/.
[src:approximant/alveolar-consonant] (Samoan words written with *t* and *n* are pronounced with [k] and [ŋ] in colloquial speech.) In Standard Hawaiian, [t] is an allophone of /k/, but /l/ and /n/ exist.
[src:approximant/alveolar-ejective-affricate] An **alveolar ejective affricate** is a type of consonantal sound, used in some spoken languages.
[src:approximant/alveolar-ejective-affricate] The symbol in the International Phonetic Alphabet that represents this sound is ⟨t͡sʼ⟩ or ⟨t͜sʼ⟩.
[src:approximant/approximant] Before Peter Ladefoged coined the term *approximant* in the 1960s, the terms *frictionless continuant* and *semivowel* were used to refer to non-lateral approximants.
[src:approximant/approximant] As a distinctive feature, *approximant* has also sometimes been expanded to encompass vowels in addition to semivowels (glides) and liquids.
[src:approximant/approximant] Some approximants resemble vowels in acoustic and articulatory properties and the terms *semivowel* and *glide* are often used for these non-syllabic vowel-like segments.
[src:approximant/approximant] The correlation between semivowels and vowels is strong enough that cross-language differences between semivowels correspond with the differences between their related vowels.
[src:approximant/approximant] Semivowels may be distinguished from the rest of approximants via a feature of *prolongability*; while all other approximants are *prolongable*, semivowels are *momentary*, as prolonging them results instead in the formation of their vocalic equivalents ([j, w] → [i, u]).
[src:approximant/approximant] Vowels and their corresponding semivowels alternate in many languages depending on the phonological environment, or for grammatical reasons, as is the case with Indo-European ablaut.
[src:approximant/approximant] Similarly, languages often avoid configurations where a semivowel precedes its corresponding vowel.
[src:approximant/approximant] A number of phoneticians distinguish between semivowels and approximants by their location in a syllable.
[src:approximant/approximant] Although he uses the terms interchangeably, Montreuil (2004, p.
[src:approximant/approximant] 104) remarks that, for example, the final glides of English *par* and *buy* differ from French *par* ('through') and *baille* ('tub') in that in the French examples, the approximants appear in the syllable coda, whereas in the English ones, they appear in the syllable nucleus.
[src:approximant/approximant] In a related sense, the terms *semivowel* and *semiconsonant* are often treated as synonyms in English linguistic tradition, though the latter may be regarded as somewhat antiquated.
[src:approximant/approximant] However, in other linguistic traditions, a distinction is made between the two terms.
[src:approximant/approximant] In these traditions, *semivowels* refer to non-syllabic vowel offglides (such as [i̯, u̯]) often found as components of syllable nuclei (such as in diphthongs), while *semiconsonants* refer to consonant onglides (such as [j, w]) often found in syllable onsets.
[src:approximant/approximant] An example demonstrating this difference can be observed in the interjections ***y**a**y*** [ˈjei̯] and ***w**o**w*** [ˈwau̯].
[src:approximant/approximant] The following table demonstrates vowel correspondences with associated approximants.
[src:approximant/approximant] The § rhotic approximants listed here are not widely considered to be semivowels, but are provided as they do map to corresponding vowels.
[src:approximant/approximant] Because of the articulatory complexities of the American English rhotic, there is some variation in its phonetic description.
[src:approximant/approximant] Actual retroflexion may occur as well and both occur as variations of the same sound.
[src:approximant/approximant] However, these sounds generally have little or no lip-spreading.
[src:approximant/approximant] Although many languages have central vowels [ɨ, ʉ], which lie between back/velar [ɯ, u] and front/palatal [i, y], there are few cases of a corresponding approximant [ ȷ̈, ɥ̈] (or equivalently [ɰ̈, ẅ]).
[src:approximant/approximant] It has been noted that the expected symbols for the approximant correlates of [ɨ, ʉ] are ⟨ɉ, w̶⟩, ⟨ɉ, ɥ̶⟩, or ⟨ɰ̶, ɥ̶⟩ (as such, the correlate vowels may also be transcribed as ⟨ɯ̶, ɏ⟩).
[src:approximant/approximant] An additional distinction of roundedness type may also be made between [ɥ̈ / ɥ̶] and [ẅ / w̶]: the former being compressed, and the latter protruded (the same distinction may be applied to [ÿ / ɏ] and [ʉ]).
[src:approximant/approximant] One might also distinguish [ ȷ̈ / ɉ] and [ɰ̈ / ɰ̶] by slight degrees of fronting and backing (and by extension, [ɨ] and [ɯ̈ / ɯ̶]), thus being referred to as *post-palatal* and *pre-velar*, respectively.
[src:approximant/approximant] In articulation and often diachronically, palatal approximants correspond to front vowels, velar approximants to back vowels, and labialized approximants to rounded vowels.
[src:approximant/approximant] In American English, the rhotic approximant corresponds to the rhotic vowel.
[src:approximant/approximant] This can create alternations (as shown in the above table).
[src:approximant/approximant] In addition to alternations, glides can be inserted to the left or the right of their corresponding vowels when they occur next to a hiatus.
[src:approximant/approximant] Similarly, vowels can be inserted next to their corresponding glide in certain phonetic environments.
[src:approximant/approximant] Sievers' law describes this behaviour for Germanic.
[src:approximant/approximant] In colloquial Nepali speech, a process of glide-formation occurs, where one of two adjacent vowels becomes non-syllabic; the process includes mid vowels so that [dʱo̯a] ('cause to wish') features a non-syllabic mid vowel.
[src:approximant/approximant] Spanish features a similar process and even nonsyllabic /a/ can occur so that *ahorita* ('right away') is pronounced [a̯o̞ˈɾita].
[src:approximant/approximant] It is not often clear, however, whether such sequences involve a semivowel (a consonant) or a diphthong (a vowel), and in many cases, it may not be a meaningful distinction.
[src:approximant/approximant] According to their standard definitions, approximants (such as [j]) contrast with fricatives (such as [ʝ]) in that fricatives produce turbulence, but approximants do not.
[src:approximant/approximant] In addition to less turbulence, approximants also differ from fricatives in the precision required to produce them.
[src:approximant/approximant] When emphasized, approximants may be slightly fricated (that is, the airstream may become slightly turbulent), which is reminiscent of fricatives.
[src:approximant/approximant] However, such frication is generally slight and intermittent, unlike the strong turbulence of fricative consonants.
[src:approximant/approximant] In discussing Spanish, Martínez-Celdrán (2004) suggested setting up a category of **spirant approximants** (such as [ʝ̞]) contrasting with both semivowel approximants and fricatives, described as "non-rhotic central approximants".
[src:approximant/approximant] The term has since been used with regularity by Martínez-Celdrán and other authors, particularly when discussing the phonetics of Spanish and other Iberian languages such as Galician.
[src:approximant/approximant] Ball & Rahilly (2011) revived the term "frictionless continuant" – which historically referred more broadly to non-lateral approximants – to distinguish this same class, and continued to use the term in subsequent works.
[src:approximant/approximant] However, as Ball (2026a) notes, both the *spirant* and *frictionless continuant* terminologies suffer from some level of ambiguity, as they both recall older (albeit now mostly disused) definitions with subtle differences from their current meaning.
[src:approximant/approximant] Other names that have been used for this class invoke fricatives, with prefix modifiers such as "weak", "approximated", and "lenited".
[src:approximant/approximant] No dominant and preferred term has yet emerged, but for simplicity, this page uses *spirant approximants*.
[src:approximant/approximant] The class includes all non-rhotic, non-lateral, non-semivowel approximants.
[src:approximant/approximant] They remain distinct from fricatives in having the characteristic non-turbulent (laminar) airflow of approximants.
[src:approximant/approximant] Though spirant approximants are more constricted (having a lower *F*2 amplitude), longer, and unspecified for rounding (*viuda* [ˈb**ju**ða] 'widow' vs.
[src:approximant/approximant] *ayuda* [aˈ**ʝʷu**ða] 'help'), the distributional overlap is limited.
[src:approximant/approximant] Spirant approximants can only appear in syllable onset (including word-initially, where semivowels never appear).
[src:approximant/approximant] The two overlap in distribution after /l/ and /n/: *enyesar* [ẽɲ**ɟʝ**eˈsaɾ] ('to plaster') vs.
[src:approximant/approximant] *aniego* [ãˈn**j**eɣo] 'flood', and although there is dialectal and idiolectal variation, speakers may also exhibit other near-minimal pairs like *ab**y**ecto* [aβ̞ˈ**ʝ**e̞tːo̞] 'abject' vs.
[src:approximant/approximant] One potential minimal pair (depending on dialect) is *ya visto* [**(ɟ)ʝa**ˈβisto] 'already seen' vs.
[src:approximant/approximant] *y ha visto* [**ja**ˈβisto] 'and he has seen'.
[src:approximant/approximant] The feature is not present in all dialects of Spanish.
[src:approximant/approximant] The syllabic fricatives found in some languages (sometimes referred to as "apical vowels", particularly in Sinological circles, as they behave like vowels phonologically) have also been reported to have similar features to spirant approximants, being approximant-like in their articulation.
[src:approximant/approximant] For places of articulation further back in the mouth, from uvular to epiglottal (which may be grouped under the umbrella term guttural consonants), languages do not contrast voiced fricatives and approximants.
[src:approximant/approximant] Therefore, the assigned symbols in the IPA for the voiced fricatives of these places are typically also used for the approximants, and often without a lowering diacritic.
[src:approximant/approximant] Occasionally, the glottal "fricatives" are described as approximants, since [h] typically has no more frication than voiceless approximants (described in the section below), but they are often segmental phonations of the glottis without any accompanying manner or place of articulation.
[src:approximant/approximant] There has historically been some controversy over whether **voiceless approximants** can exist.
[src:approximant/approximant] In contrast, more recent research distinguishes between turbulent (fricative-like) and laminar (vowel- or approximant-like) airflow in the vocal tract, with voiced fricatives characterized by more strongly turbulent airflow than voiceless fricatives due to tighter glottal constriction.
[src:approximant/approximant] As such, voiceless approximants are rarely, if ever, distinguished phonemically from voiceless fricatives in the sound system of a language.
[src:approximant/approximant] Fricative consonants are generally said to be the result of turbulent airflow at a place of articulation in the vocal tract.
[src:approximant/approximant] However, an audible voiceless sound may be made without this turbulent airflow: Pike (1943) makes a distinction between "local friction" (as in [s] or [z]) and "cavity friction" (as in voiceless vowels like [ḁ] and [ɔ̥]).
[src:approximant/approximant] More recent research distinguishes between "turbulent" and "laminar" airflow in the vocal tract.
[src:approximant/approximant] It is not clear if it is possible to describe voiceless approximants categorically as having laminar airflow (or cavity friction in Pike's terms) as a way of distinguishing them from fricatives.
[src:approximant/approximant] Ball & Rahilly (1999) write that "the airflow for voiced approximants remains laminar (smooth), and does not become turbulent.
[src:approximant/approximant] Voiceless approximants are treated as a phonetic category by (among others) Catford (1982) [1977], Ladefoged & Maddieson (1996), and Bickford & Floyd (2006).
[src:approximant/approximant] However, the term *voiceless approximant* is seen by some phoneticians as controversial.
[src:approximant/approximant] It has been pointed out that if *approximant* is defined as a speech sound that involves the articulators approaching each other but not narrowly enough to create turbulent airflow, then it is difficult to see how a *voiceless* approximant could be audible.
[src:approximant/approximant] Asu, Nolan & Schötz (2015) compared voiceless laterals in Estonian Swedish, Icelandic, and Welsh and found that Welsh-speakers consistently used [ɬ], that Icelandic-speakers consistently used [l̥], and that speakers of Estonian Swedish varied in their pronunciation.
[src:approximant/approximant] They conclude that there is "a range of variants within voiceless laterals, rather than a categorical split between lateral fricatives and voiceless approximant laterals".
[src:approximant/approximant] Ball (2026a) reiterates that "it is a matter of debate as to whether voiceless equivalents of approximants can still be considered approximants or whether they should be termed fricatives".
[src:approximant/approximant] According to Ball, the arguments in favor of the recognition of voiceless approximants can be broken down into two primary positions: from a phonological standpoint, and from a phonetic one.
[src:approximant/approximant] The phonological position is one of "economical" explanations when addressing voiceless allophones of approximants in restricted environments.
[src:approximant/approximant] For example, it is simplest to describe only the devoicing of approximants within consonant clusters when preceded by voiceless consonants in English, such as in the words *p**l**ay* [pl̥eɪ] and *p**r**ay* [pɹ̥eɪ], rather than additionally describing changes in manner of articulation.
[src:approximant/approximant] The phonetic position focuses on the distinction of turbulent versus laminar airflow, as described above.
[src:approximant/approximant] The phonetic features that define rhotic consonants are not well understood, despite many attempts to establish their unification.
[src:approximant/approximant] Instead, they are largely understood to be unified by their orthographic representation, such as with ⟨R r⟩ in Latin scripts, ⟨Ρ ρ⟩ in Greek scripts, and ⟨Р р⟩ in Cyrillic scripts.
[src:approximant/approximant] Similarly, within the IPA, rhotics are typically represented with a variety of symbols derived from the Latin letter ⟨R r⟩; in their unmarked forms (without diacritics), they represent a range of articulatory manners, including trills, taps, fricatives, and approximants.
[src:approximant/approximant] Nonetheless, there have been multiple studies showing their perceptual unity as a natural class, as well as to some extent their acoustic and phonological similarities.
[src:approximant/approximant] Furthermore, rhotics exhibit a degree of unity through contrast: they are distinctive enough for other consonant types to be defined as "non-rhotic", such as the § spirant approximants described above.
[src:approximant/approximant] Studies have also suggested that sulcalization may play an important role in defining rhotics.
[src:approximant/approximant] The most widely recognized rhotic approximants are alveolar [ɹ], retroflex [ɻ], and uvular [ʁ̞], along with their postalveolar [ɹ̠] and velar [ɹ̈] analogues.
[src:approximant/approximant] These approximants often exhibit free variation with one another, such as in English and in Dutch, though their target places of articulation may also be more stable in other languages.
[src:approximant/approximant] No language has been well-established to have a phonemic distinction between any two of these rhotic approximants.
[src:approximant/approximant] However, despite the widespread lack of a phonemic distinction between the typical rhotic approximants, many languages have a phonemic contrast between at least two general rhotic consonants; a well-known example is a contrast between a tap /ɾ/ and a trill /r/.
[src:approximant/approximant] In Spanish, these are typically distinguished in orthography with ⟨r⟩ for the tap and ⟨rr⟩ for the trill (though the trill may also appear in some words with a singular ⟨r⟩, and ⟨rr⟩ may be reduced to a tap in some environments).
[src:approximant/approximant] As described in the § spirants section above, Spanish is also well-known for its lenition (weakening) of plosive and fricative consonants to approximant ones (as are several other Romance languages), such as /b, d, ʝ, ɡ/ to [β̞, ð̞, ʝ̞, ɣ̞].
[src:approximant/approximant] It has been reported by several authors that this lenition is extended to the tap and trill in some environments for multiple varieties of Spanish, where /ɾ, r/ become [ɾ̞, r̞], being referred to as an *approximant tap* and *approximant trill*, respectively.
[src:approximant/approximant] Thus, taking into account these allophones, a distinction between two rhotic approximants does exist in some languages.
[src:approximant/approximant] Authors have occasionally used the terms "nasal approximants" and "nasalized approximants" to describe sounds with varying degrees of nasality.
[src:approximant/approximant] The distinction may be transcribed as a nasal occlusive with a downtack (such as ⟨n̞, ŋ᫛, ɴ̞⟩) for nasal approximants, and an approximant with a combining tilde above (such as ⟨ɹ̃, ɰ̃, ʁ̞̃⟩) for nasalized approximants.
[src:approximant/approximant] For simplicity and to avoid diacritic stacking, § glottalic approximants are only shown with a preceding superscript, as in ⟨ˀw⟩.
[src:approximant/approximant] However, this should not be interpreted as preglottalization being the only realization of these sounds.
[src:approximant/approximant] Generally speaking, as with all glottalic sonorants, the timing of glottalization for approximants is fluid.
[src:approximant/approximant] Additionally, the § labial and § glottal approximants are grouped with the § median approximants as they also apply to the § spirant subclass, though they are not actually median consonants as they do not involve the tongue as an articulator.
[src:approximant/approximant] The approximant tap and approximant trill § rhotics are grouped with their standard alveolar rhotic approximant counterpart, as no other configurations of these kinds have been reported.
[src:approximant/approximant] For some configurations, letters shown with the lowered diacritic ⟨˕⟩ are often transcribed without it; the diacritic is used here to distinguish from their fricative counterparts.
